      "content": "Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship 37 captures 29 Dec 2015 - 18 Jun 2023 Feb MAR Apr 28 2018 2019 2020 success fail About this capture COLLECTED BY Collection: Wikipedia Eventstream TIMESTAMPS The Wayback Machine - https://web.archive.org/web/20190328063543/https://publications.mi.byu.edu/book/enoch-the-prophet/ LOGIN | HELP | About WATCH THE FILM The Neal A. Maxwell Institute: By Study and Also By Faith Advisory Board About Elder Neal A. Maxwell Fellowships &#038; Grants Nibley Fellowship Program Swensen Mentorships Annual Report Current (2018) Past Reports Personnel Institute Scholars Past Visiting Scholars Staff Past Student Staff Events Publications LATEST RELEASE An Early Resurrection , by Adam Miller Periodicals Studies in the Bible and Antiquity Journal of Book of Mormon Studies Books Living Faith Books Groundwork Series Scriptures Made Harder Series Authors Past Publications Middle Eastern Texts Initiative Mormon Theology Seminar Mormon Studies Review FARMS Preliminary Reports FARMS Review (1989-2011) Occasional Papers (2000-2007) Insights Newsletter (1981-2013) Other Materials Summer Seminar on Mormon Culture Study of Mormon Studies Bibliography Bushman Colloquium Transcripts Multimedia Subscribe Podcast LATEST EPISODE #90—Editing and illuminating the Book of Mormon, with Grant Hardy and Brian Kershisnik MIPodcast Home All Episodes Transcripts MIPodcast Moments Subscribe in iTunes Listen on YouTube Stitcher Radio Newsletter Past Editions Subscribe Laura F. Willes Center Enoch the Prophet / Publications / Books / Enoch the Prophet Enoch the Prophet Hugh Nibley 1986 In the Book of Moses, part of the Latter-day Saint scriptural canon known as the Pearl of Great Price, are what the Prophet Joseph Smith entitled “extracts from the prophecy of Enoch.” These scriptures, says the eminent LDS scholar Hugh Nibley, “supply us with the most valuable control yet on the bona fides of the Prophet. . . . We are to test. . . . ‘How does it compare with records known to be authentic?’ The excerpts offer the nearest thing to a perfectly foolproof test—neat, clear-cut, and decisive—of Joseph Smith’s claim to inspiration.” In Enoch the Prophet , Dr. Nibley examines and defends that claim by examining Joseph Smith’s translations in the context of recently discovered apocryphal sources. This second volume in Nibley’s collected works includes four chapters: “Enoch the Prophet,” “The Enoch Figure,” “The Book of Enoch as Theodicy,” and “A Strange Thing in the Land: The Return of the Book of Enoch.” Read Online --> --> Subject Categories hugh-nibley Table of Contents Publication Information About the Author Table of Contents Foreword By Stephen D. Ricks Enoch the Prophet The Enoch Figure The Book of Enoch as a Theodicy A Strange Thing in the Land: The Return of the Book of Enoch—Part 1 A Strange Thing in the Land: The Return of the Book of Enoch—Part 2 Publication Information Publication Date: 1986 ISBN 13: 978-0875790473 Page Count: 320 Size: 6x9 Binding: Hardcover Price: $ 35.95 Series: Collected Works of Hugh Nibley Imprint: Deseret Book, FARMS Hugh Nibley A new \"Nibley Library\" page is currently under construction that will feature Nibley treasures untold. In the meantime, here's a list of Nibley's contributions to FARMS and the Maxwell Institute over the years. Hugh Nibley was one of the most gifted scholars in the LDS Church. He graduated summa cum laude from UCLA and completed his PhD as a University Fellow at UC Berkeley. He taught at Claremont College in California before serving in military intelligence in World War II. From 1946 until his death in 2005, he was associated with and taught at Brigham Young University. Read More VIEW MORE &#8593; Subscribe to Our Blog Email * Copyright © 2014 Brigham Young University All Rights Reserved The views expressed in Maxwell Institute publications are those of the individual authors and do not necessarily represent the position of the Maxwell Institute, Brigham Young University, or The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.",
